  "opinion": "As a retired woman from Kansas City with a vocational diploma and a lifetime of observing the world through both garden and board games, I’ve seen how science can be a bridge between curiosity and community. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about the stories we tell ourselves. My parents, one with a bachelor’s degree and the other only with primary education, taught me that science isn’t reserved for the privileged few. When I was young, my father would take me to the local library to read about stars and planets, while my mother helped me measure garden plots with a ruler. Those early moments showed me that science is accessible to all, but it’s often shaped by the doors we don’t see. In today’s world, the gap persists because we still talk about science in ways that exclude voices of color, women, and those from underfunded schools. But it’s not too late to fix it. I’ve seen how creative problem-solving—like designing a garden that grows food for neighbors—can spark interest in science without the pressure of formal labs. We need to bring science back to the community, to the kitchen, to the playground, where everyone can ask questions without fear. Addressing the gap means creating spaces where curiosity is celebrated, not constrained by stereotypes. It starts with listening to the children who are already asking ‘why’—the ones who don’t fit the mold of the traditional scientist. By nurturing that spark, we can build a future where science serves everyone, not just the few.",
